ariant of <b>Panting</b>, itself a variant of either   Penton   or   Panton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ponton","meanings":["Scottish and English: habitational name, probably from Great and Little Ponton in Lincolnshire, perhaps named from an obscure Old English word <i>pamp</i> ‘hill’ or <i>panne</i> ‘pan’ (in a transferred topographic sense ‘depression, hollow’) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead’, ‘enclosure’.","English: occasionally a variant of   Ponting  ."]},{"name":"Penton","meanings":["English (mainly Hampshire):","habitational name from Penton Grafton or Penton Mewsey (both Hanmpshire), or from a shortened form of   Pennington   2. The placenames denoted a farm or estate for which a penny tax was payable (Old English <i>pening</i> ‘penny’ + <i>tūn</i>).","in north-west England, a shortened form of   Pennington   1, from either of the places called Pennington in Lancashire."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":37,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Punting was born in 1418, in Badingham, Suffolk, England. She married Robert F. Derehaugh in 1444, in Badingham, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1480, in her hometown, at the age of 62, and was buried in Badingham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1418–1480":"1418–1480","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1447–Female":"1447–Surnud","1449–Female":"1449–Surnud","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","about 1449":"umbes 1449","about 1447":"umbes 1447","1496":"1496","1473":"1473","19 May 1473":"19. mai 1473","1480":"1480","1418":"1418","1449":"1449","St. John the Baptist Churchyard, Badingham. Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, England","Badingham, Suffolk Coastal District, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1418–1480":"1418–1480","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1447–Female":"1447–Kuollut","1449–Female":"1449–Kuollut","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","about 1449":"noin 1449","about 1447":"noin 1447","1496":"1496","1473":"1473","19 May 1473":"19. toukokuuta 1473","1480":"1480","1418":"1418","1449":"1449","St. John the Baptist Churchyard, Badingham. Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Badingham, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, England","Badingham, Suffolk Coastal District, Suffolk, England":"Badingham, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1418–1480":"1418–1480","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1445–1496":"1445–1496","1447–Female":"1447–Décédée","1449–Female":"1449–Décédée","1447":"1447","1445":"1445","1444":"